{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":301246,"duration_api_ms":285054,"num_turns":52,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"ab507ecc-d4f2-4275-9260-cf0d7fde8197","total_cost_usd":2.02186925,"usage":{"input_tokens":43,"cache_creation_input_tokens":75563,"cache_read_input_tokens":2707871,"output_tokens":7818,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":75563,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":43,"outputTokens":7818,"cacheReadInputTokens":2707871,"cacheCreationInputTokens":75563,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":2.02186925,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed the full diff (13 files changed) implementing retry hardening: increased retry limits, hard timeout enforcement on process/tmux backends, BinaryNotFound failure class for terminal exit codes, exponential backoff in the engine retry loop. All 678 tests pass, clippy clean. The implementation is well-structured with proper cancellation handling, artifact preservation on timeout, and a service-level safety-net timeout with 30s buffer. Found one moderate correctness concern and one minor robustness gap.","amendments":[{"body":"In `process_backend.rs` timeout path (~line 1048-1049), `spawn_background_reap` is called to kill the child but the `prepared.preserve_failed_artifacts()` is only called later in the `invoke()` method (~line 1230-1233), not in `spawn_and_wait()`. This means the `spawn_and_wait()` timeout path returns the error *without* cleaning up temp files (schema/message paths for Codex). The cleanup happens at the caller level, which is correct. However, if `spawn_and_wait()` is ever called from a different call site that doesn't handle the Timeout failure_class specially, temp files will leak. Consider moving `prepared.preserve_failed_artifacts()` into a single cleanup path or documenting the cleanup contract more explicitly so future callers don't miss it.","rationale":"Defense in depth: the current code works because the two call sites (primary invoke and stale-session retry) both check for Timeout. But the split responsibility between spawn_and_wait (kills process) and invoke (preserves artifacts) is fragile if new call sites are added."},{"body":"The backoff `backoff_for_attempt(cursor.attempt)` is called with the *current* attempt number (1-indexed, starting at 1) before `cursor.retry()` increments it. This means the very first retry (after attempt 1 fails) waits 5 seconds. For the common case of a transient JSON parse error that would succeed immediately on retry, this adds unnecessary latency. Consider using `backoff_for_attempt(cursor.attempt - 1)` or starting the base delay at attempt 2 so the first retry is immediate and backoff kicks in only on repeated failures.","rationale":"In production runs with 20+ rounds, a single transient failure is the most common case. Adding 5s to every single first-retry adds up. The exponential backoff is most valuable for repeated failures hitting rate limits, not for one-off glitches."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"08264445-2884-4c5f-9e6b-38e1a8ef7f71"}
